<HEADLINE>
<P>
ON TOP OF EVERYTHING; 
</P>
<P>
BRIGHT OR NEUTRAL, LONG OR SHORT, IT'S THE JACKET THAT REALLY COUNTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BARBARA FOLEY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WHEN DISCUSSING summer wardrobes, designers in Milan, Paris, New York and 
Southern California agree: Keep the underpinnings basic (a unitard will do), 
and make the jacket exciting. 
</P>
<P>
Whether chartreuse, orange, chrome yellow or warm white, today's jackets are 
colorful. 
</P>
<P>
They're also roomy and relaxed but not sloppy. Armani shows long, 
East-Indian-inspired, tissue-weight jackets, while Chanel's are shorter and 
gently shaped. Donna Karan has designed sleek, fluid styles, and those by 
California designers range from short and boxy to long and lean. 
</P>
<P>
Detailing is important: Waists may be nipped in with belts, shirring and curvy 
seaming; buttons are often decorative, and collar and pocket treatments create 
subtle novelty touches. 
</P>
<P>
This jacket wardrobe is exceptional in every way except price -- each jacket is 
under $300. 
</P>
<P>
Model: Holly Kimsey/Mary Webb Davis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, COLOR, Anne Klein II white crepe blazer, right, $288, at I. Magnin; gold 
hat by Kokin, $130, at Privilege, Beverly Center and Westside Pavilion; A.B.S. 
Unitard jumpsuit (in all photos), $122, at Saks Fifth Avenue. L. Bates 
leaf-green belted jacket, left, $178, at Saks Fifth Avenue; Kokin scarf, $250, 
Neiman Marcus. Dana Buchman orange sweater-jacket, top, $178, at Saks Fifth 
Avenue; Donna Karan sunglasses, $165, at Bullock's. Kirk McKoy 
