<HEADLINE>
<P>
ALICE KAHN: NEW, USED DREAMS FOR SALE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALICE KAHN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For us, the dream is over. We sold out and someone from Los Angeles bought it. 
Why not? The property is only a 700-mile drive for the new owner. 
</P>
<P>
According to the lore, anyone living between Guadalajara and Anchorage lives in 
terror of being taken over by Californians, a fact celebrated in bumper 
stickers that say, "Don't Californicate Oregon." Portland and Seattle have 
become hot spots of these real estate ravishment fantasies. But even quiet 
little towns in central and northern California such as San Luis Obispo and 
Mendocino seem worried. 
</P>
<P>
Of course, when the locals speak of the Californians they fear, they are not 
referring to tweedy, ecologically minded, culturally sensitive San Franciscans. 
The nightmare is hordes of muscular blondes in fluorescent bras on 
roller-skates together with tan, hairless-chested surfer boys on bodyboards 
careening down Main Street. 
</P>
<P>
The locals also fear the couple who drive up in front of the 
Victorian-plus-five-acres in their powder-blue Mercedes 450SL. Will the 
visitors get on their cellular phone and say, "One eighty-nine five? Is all 
cash OK?" 
</P>
<P>
The monsters in the Mercedes are the modern Attila: Rich Invading People from 
L.A. RIPLAs are unwanted by everyone. Except the sellers. 
</P>
<P>
Even rumors that rich people from L.A. are in an area can send real estate 
prices higher than a palm tree on a Beverly Hills lawn. Just a whiff of Robin 
Williams in the air sent real estate prices soaring in Gualala, a tiny coastal 
town. Ditto with Sylvester Stallone in a remote part of Maui. If he wanted to, 
Jack Nicholson alone could boost Portland prices 25% overnight. 
</P>
<P>
I don't think Nigel Fingerman is actually rich. All I know about him is that he 
lives in L.A., he has something to do with the music business, he made us an 
offer, and he now owns our dream. 
</P>
<P>
The dream we sold to Nigel was 20 acres of raw land with what is known as a 
"blue water view." That means the Pacific Ocean sits out there like a mirage -- 
too far to walk to, too beautiful to walk away from. You can't really walk 
anywhere because the land is densely forested except for the deer trails and 
the old dirt logging road that leads you to it. There's no water, no power and 
no people. All there is is a place to imagine. 
</P>
<P>
Imagine a cabin here. Imagine if we find a spring there. Imagine a little 
garden here. Imagine a play structure there. 
</P>
<P>
When we bought the land 10 years ago, our dream was this: We would go up every 
weekend despite many hours driving on the twisted coastal highway with a 
carsickness-prone child. ("Prone" here means you pull over in terror every time 
she coughs.) We would improve the land but still keep its natural character. 
(Ha! How little we understood nature's imperative to maintain her own overgrown 
self.) Eventually we would retire there and live like Ma and Pa Hippie Kettle, 
sleeping by moon, cooking by wood, taking only what we needed, back to the 
land. 
</P>
<P>
In 1980, one still had these pre-Reagan visions. 
</P>
<P>
My husband and I forgot one thing: We were city people. Our parents had 
struggled to get away from the land they came from and get to the city, where 
they could earn a living and buy some luxuries like a refrigerator. 
</P>
<P>
One other problem: We had no skills and no tools (except the checkbook). And we 
had no time to acquire them. We hardly had time to drive up there. We were too 
busy working the jobs that allowed us to indulge in a 20-acre dream. 
</P>
<P>
As dreams go, it wasn't all that expensive. Less than a time-share. Way less 
than a house -- even in Portland. Less than even the cheapest Mercedes. 
</P>
<P>
So, we got a little trailer up there and kept it stocked with all the 
necessities -- dishes, diapers, fresh roast coffee. For a few years, we went up 
maybe 10 times a summer. Then the kids got bigger and work got more hectic and 
we had what is known as "scheduling problems." 
</P>
<P>
Nature soon let us know that unless we planned to stay there and fight her, she 
would reclaim the land. We would have to regrade the dirt road. We'd have to 
evict the critters in the trailer. We'd have to keep clearing the trails we had 
cleared. We'd have to cut trees to keep the view. Someone suggested we get us 
some marijuana sharecroppers to maintain the land. 
</P>
<P>
Instead, we sold to Nigel Fingerman of Los Angeles, making no money on the 
deal. If we had put the money in a passbook account at a crumbling S&amp;L, 
we'd have done better. 
</P>
<P>
Yet, I'm not even sure why we sold it. I think we just felt like jerks as we 
realized how far our fantasy was from reality. 
</P>
<P>
The day after we signed the paper giving Nigel Fingerman permission to act out 
on our dreamscape, all the newspapers reported that a movie star had bought a 
house down the road and real estate prices in the area were expected to jump. 
Did Nigel know something from the old L.A. Dudes Network or was it just our bad 
luck? 
</P>
<P>
When we bought the land in 1980 with our earnest chunk of cash and our 
infatuation with redwoods/ocean/sun, the agent said in all candor, "I sell new 
and used dreams." 
</P>
<P>
Ours is used up now, and the land is more natural than we found it. This land 
was our land, this land is Fingerman's land -- until the next used-dream sale. 
</P>
<P>
All I'm saying is that if you're in the north woods and see a guy in Ray-Bans 
and a Lakers T-shirt gathering twigs and carrying a bucket of water, give that 
ugly Californian his chance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
