<HEADLINE>
<P>
HEALTH-CARE CRISIS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Thanks to Jonathan Freedman for his two-part series, "No Care Mothers -- No 
Hope Babies," (Commentary, May 15-16). It was a good start at touching on the 
health-care crisis we presently have in this state, as well as country. What he 
failed to point out was that even insured babies can be doomed by the system. 
</P>
<P>
My children were planned and born into an insured, loving environment. When my 
eldest daughter was 3, she was operated on for a blocked kidney. One can hardly 
find the words to describe the range of emotions a parent goes through when 
something of that magnitude happens to her child. The only thing that allowed 
us some peace of mind was that we had good health coverage, which enabled her 
the best care available. Little did we realize that the true crisis was yet to 
begin. 
</P>
<P>
Today, four years later, our daughter happily runs and plays, her world filled 
with kittens, school and friends. Today, we, her parents, face having her 
uninsured. Our insurance company has raised our rates 100% every year, to the 
current rate of $9,000 a year. And looming ahead -- $18,000? 
</P>
<P>
We have a stack of rejection letters from other health insurers. They will 
insure everyone but our eldest. She cannot qualify for Medi-Cal because they 
take into account her parents' salary. Ironically, our taxes help fund this. 
Unfortunately she (we) are neither rich enough to continue paying what amounts 
to blackmail, nor poor enough to qualify for assistance. 
</P>
<P>
Health rights are survival rights. There are no easy answers. Politicians often 
use the phrase "the children are our future." But where is their future without 
the right to medical care? We need to be advocates for the basic rights of all 
children or we end up with a separatist, discriminatory state. Children caught 
in the bind of "pre-existing" conditions face a dark, uncertain future. 
</P>
<P>
KATHLEEN RENSHAW-HARVEY 
</P>
<P>
Leucadia 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
