<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA061090-0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 231541 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
June 10, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Book Review; Page 3; Book Review Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
998 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
A PAPER GUY TO CALL HER OWN; 
</P>
<P>
REACHING TIN RIVER BY THEA ASTLEY (G.P. PUTNAM'S SONS: $18.95; 224 PP.; 
0-399-13532-4) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Judith Freeman, Freeman is the author of a novel, The Chinchilla Farm, and a 
collection of short stories, Family Attractions. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
There is no landscape like the landscape of childhood, terrain at once vivid 
and terrifyingly vague. Thea Astley understands this well, how the sounds of 
teacups being refilled, a grandfather's mumbled comments, or the smell of a 
handful of gum leaves remain fixed in the brain years later as if they were the 
most important moments in one's life, the strongest memory of love. 
</P>
<P>
At first, "Reaching Tin River" seems as if it's going to be a novel about this 
-- a childhood in the magical kingdom of Queensland, North Australia. Not that 
life is idyllic there on the burnt, raw land. "I want love," her small heroine, 
Belle, sobs, and we think it's because she's been uprooted from her beloved 
home and sent to a boarding school; also because she's a fatherless child, 
reared by aging grandparents, a daffy drum-banging mother and a piano-playing 
aunt who form an all-women's band, a duo "welded into a partnership stronger 
than marriage, a kind of twinhood sanctified and integrated by cornball 
rhythms," much more concerned with thumping out "sugar-candy tunes" than 
attending to a small girl's needs. 
</P>
<P>
The novel ends up being about a much different thing, however, namely the adult 
Belle's obsessive search for a "center," a quest that causes her to go off the 
emotional deep end and adopt a "paper lover," a figure out of history named 
Gaden Lockyer whose face she first discovers in the archives of a library where 
she works. Yet the childhood that failed little Belle out on Perjury Plains 
(the telling name of the family property) in the final analysis seems immutably 
connected to her fractured, distressed adulthood. For one thing, she never 
stops looking for love. 
</P>
<P>
Thea Astley -- three-time winner of the Miles Franklin Award, Australia's 
highest literary honor, and author of 10 previous novels and a collection of 
short stories -- is a most original writer whose sentences seem charged with 
incendiary power and whose insight into social mores -- especially the 
relations between men and women -- have a dead-on rightness. Reading her last 
book to appear here, "Two by Astley," a volume containing two novellas 
originally published in Australia in the 1970s, one couldn't help being deeply 
impressed by the energy and intelligence of her writing. The first novella: "A 
Kindness Cup," the story of an aboriginal massacre and its effect years later 
on the inhabitants of a small town, seemed the better work, though it was in 
"The Acolyte" that Astley's social wit and her pyrotechnic flare for language 
was most evident. 
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, neither talent -- not the story-telling ability nor the 
beautifully charged language -- is employed with the same success in "Reaching 
Tin River." The novel feels hurried, as if written in a rush. Its tone is 
rather conversational. 
</P>
<P>
Not that Astley is capable of writing badly. The wit, the unerring social 
observations, still come through, and the novel has wonderful vignettes -- a 
girl in a bathing suit tantalizing an older man; a mother weaving "red setter" 
place mats out of her dog's hair. But the well-crafted plot of "A Kindness 
Cup," the controlled character revelations found in "The Acolyte" -- these have 
been scrapped for a breezier, faster sort of book about the obsessional Belle, 
a character who at the book's end has gone to extremes that don't make sense. 
</P>
<P>
Belle's American serviceman father, Huck, knew her mother, Bonnie, only long 
enough to conceive a child and take her off to San Diego for a few months 
before Bonnie packed up and headed back to Queensland, though why the marriage 
didn't work is never clear. The legacy of the brief union is Belle. When Belle 
marries a fellow librarian named Seb, she gains little more man than she lost 
in her father. Seb's a self-inflated bore, and worse, he cheats on her. By the 
time Belle realizes her marriage is done for, she has already latched onto her 
next lover, Mr. Gaden Lockyer. 
</P>
<P>
Gaden Lockyer -- no flesh-and-blood man -- is a figure out of history, a 
banker, farmer and politician who lived in Queensland at the end of the last 
century. Not handsome, but compelling in looks, he so intrigues Belle that she 
must know everything about him. Her obsession with Gaden grows, until she is 
fully engaged in "reconstructing or revivifying him." 
</P>
<P>
She has a huge photographic blowup made of his picture so that she can talk to 
him at night alone in her room and insert herself into the "picture" by 
obliterating the image of his wife. Belle sets off to track down places where 
he's lived, assuming a variety of identities until, Belle in tardy pursuit, he 
finally reached Tin River, Gaden's last abode. 
</P>
<P>
What she's really searching for is a "center." That much she makes clear. But 
what kind of a center? One within, or one without? She hopes such a center 
won't revolve around men, and maybe by creating a "paper" man Astley feels 
she's liberating her heroine, at least giving her a stepping stone. 
</P>
<P>
"Philosophically, I suppose," Belle muses, "there is little difference between 
the human center that I seek and the abstract. Modern self-indulgent psychology 
proposes that one's self is one's center, but I find the theory unsatisfying. I 
need a center in which I can merge. An alter-ego center. Isn't that what we all 
look for?" 
</P>
<P>
It's an interesting idea -- using the novel to ask this question: Where is the 
center? But the answers, the whole investigation, is too diffused here; some 
underlying fascination with Euclidean geometry is favored over an obligation to 
real emotional depth in characters. 
</P>
<P>
When Belle finally tracks down her long-lost father, making a hasty trip to the 
States to meet him in New York, their reunion is described in such a way that 
the players seem artificial. And later when Belle tells her mother she's 
located her father, there's hardly an indication of a reaction on her mother's 
part. 
</P>
<P>
Surely such a reunion would matter to both women -- matter deeply -- and a 
reader can't help but long for the emotional truth at such moments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Book Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA061090-0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 231542 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
June 10, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Book Review; Page 4; Book Review Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1256 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
AMERICA CAN STILL COMPETE; 
</P>
<P>
THE COMPETITIVE ADVANTAGE OF NATIONS BY MICHAEL E. PORTER (THE FREE 
PRESS/MACMILLAN: $35; 855 PP.; 0-02-925361-6) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Steven Schlossstein, Schlossstein, a former vice president with Morgan 
Guaranty, is president of SBS Associates, Inc., a strategic consulting firm 
based in Princeton. He is the author of The End of the American Century 
(Contemporary/Congdon &amp; Weed, 1990). 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the 1960s, American firms dominated both domestic and international markets, 
so their corporate strategies tended to focus more on personnel and less on 
product. That was the age of T-groups (T for training) and group dynamics, 
popularized by Warren Bennis and Ed Schein of MIT (later UCLA). 
</P>
<P>
Then, in the 1970s, as competitive pressure mounted from Germany and especially 
Japan, American corporations turned to a growth-share matrix, introduced by the 
Boston Consulting Group. 
</P>
<P>
The buzzwords were cash cows (for low-growth, high-market-share products), 
which fed shooting stars (high-growth, high-share), which maybe became dogs 
(low-share in a slow market) that had to be liquidated to fund the question 
marks. The acquisition craze in this era was driven partly by a desire to buy 
cash cows or shooting stars and divest the dogs. 
</P>
<P>
But in the 1980s, the matrix as an analytical tool gradually gave way to a more 
comprehensive concept called "competitive strategy," which spawned a new book 
of the very same name by Michael E. Porter of the Harvard Business School. 
</P>
<P>
Subtitled "Techniques for Analyzing Industries and Competitors" (Free 
Press/Macmillan, 1980), it established Porter as a leading practitioner of the 
art. The core of his analysis was the competitive behavior of corporations 
within their industries, and it isolated three generic strategies: low-cost 
leadership (such as IBM in computing); differentiation (e.g., Mercedes in the 
auto sector) and focus (Kodak in film). It was followed by his "Competitive 
Advantage" in 1985. 
</P>
<P>
Well, the 1990s have now begun, so it's time for another shift in the marketing 
of buzzwords. Porter is back again with another hefty tome that brings us 
concepts such as "clusters" (related and supporting industries) and the 
"diamond" of national advantage that should take us through the decade. 
</P>
<P>
His "diamond" is a complex, four-cornered diagram of what he calls 
"determinants of national competitive advantage." They include (1) corporate 
strategy, structure and rivalry; (2) factor conditions (capital, 
infrastructure, human and natural resources); (3) "clusters," and (4) demand 
conditions (the dynamics of competition in a country's domestic economy). 
</P>
<P>
"National prosperity is created, not inherited," Porter argues. "A nation's 
competitiveness depends on the capacity of its industry to innovate and to 
upgrade. Companies gain advantage . . . because of pressure and challenge. They 
benefit from having strong domestic rivals, aggressive home-based suppliers, 
and demanding local customers." 
</P>
<P>
In his new book, Porter thus deviates from the conventional wisdom of 
comparative advantage -- advanced by the traditional neoclassical economists 
such as Adam Smith and David Ricardo, who argued that it was hereditary -- and 
invites us to think instead about competitive advantage, which is created. 
</P>
<P>
Comparative advantage suggests that nations with rich factor endowments such as 
land and natural resources will be producers of agricultural commodities and 
minerals. The United States and Australia have fit this traditional paradigm 
well. 
</P>
<P>
But the neoclassical model breaks down when it comes to countries like Japan, 
which should theoretically specialize in labor-intensive goods since labor is a 
strong factor endowment. Yet as is now common knowledge, Japan rejects the 
neoclassical theory of comparative advantage and has become the leading example 
of how a nation can create its own competitive advantage: an uncompromising 
commitment to public education, a powerful trade bureaucracy and targeted 
incentives for new investment. 
</P>
<P>
The intellectual cornerstone for the theory of competitive advantage was laid 
nearly two decades ago, however, by Kazushi Ohkawa and Henry Rosovsky of 
Harvard in their seminal work "Japanese Economic Growth: Trend Acceleration in 
the 20th Century" (Stanford University Press, 1973). This original work 
(strangely unmentioned at all by Porter) cited the inherent dynamics of Japan's 
high-speed domestic economy -- not export-led growth -- as the key factor in 
its famous postwar miracle. 
</P>
<P>
Porter spent four years analyzing more than 100 companies in 10 countries to 
refine his new paradigm of competitive advantage. In his lengthy analysis, he 
applies this paradigm both to nations in various stages of development (the 
United States, Japan and Germany are included as advanced economies, with Korea 
and Singapore as industrializing models, in addition to five other European 
countries), as well as to specific industry sectors such as Italian ceramic 
tiles and Japanese robotics. 
</P>
<P>
These specific analytical studies comprise the book's real strength and most of 
its bulk. Less convincing are Porter's general implications for corporate 
strategy or government policy, which take up the final section in an attempt to 
identify national agendas for each of the countries in question. 
</P>
<P>
Particularly disappointing is his pessimistic assessment of America's own 
future, a position popular with liberals these days, especially in Cambridge 
and New Haven and Washington. "That America will remain a great power is not in 
doubt," he concludes, "the issue is whether the American economy has the 
dynamism to maintain or raise (its) standard of living, or whether the nation 
will steadily lose ground in relative terms." 
</P>
<P>
While Porter rightly isolates the many critical problems that America faces 
(flagging performance in public education, a short-term focus, lower spending 
on R&amp;D, an anemic savings rate, etc.), he falls into a common trap by not 
suggesting how we can solve them. Here, even a cursory analysis of tax-based 
incentives to strengthen R&amp;D and capital formation would have been helpful, 
or a discourse on the advantages of market-based competition and choice to help 
reform and restructure education -- unless Porter erroneously believes, as 
conventional thinkers in Cambridge and Washington do, that a national economic 
strategy or its first cousin, an industrial policy (both predicated on an 
outdated Japanese model), are viable solutions. 
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, the book's length (855 pages) and its price will be daunting for 
the general reader, who may find excerpts more appealing. While this is 
regrettable, given the book's considerable detail, both the Harvard Business 
Review (in its March-April, 1990, issue) and Fortune (March 12, 1990) offer 
abridged versions that most readers will undoubtedly prefer. But business 
schools and reference libraries will want to stock it. 
</P>
<P>
The critical question is whether one is optimistic about America's future, as I 
am (despite its present problems), or pessimistic about it, as Porter seems to 
be. Beware the permanent trend: America's great strengths as it moves toward 
the next century are an incredibly diverse and resilient society that is 
capable of unmatched entrepreneurial energy, vitality and skill; a market 
second to none in responsiveness, flexibility and size; an unparalleled 
inventiveness that will continue to drive the information revolution, and a 
dynamic heterogeneity that is being revitalized and rejuvenated by our new 
immigrants, more than half of whom now are coming from East Asia. 
</P>
<P>
These underlying strengths ought to put new and clever buzzwords into a broader 
perspective, because the T-groups and the growth-share matrix and the diamonds 
and the clusters never seem to live much beyond the fads that their short-term 
popularity creates. 
</P>
<P>
The solid building blocks of America's competitive strength, on the other hand, 
clearly will. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Book Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA061090-0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 231543 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
June 10, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Book Review; Page 6; Book Review Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
260 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
FICTION IN BRIEF: BOLSHEVIK SALUTE BY WANG MENG TRANSLATED FROM THE CHINESE BY 
WENDY LARSON (UNIVERSITY OF WASHINGTON PRESS: $19.95; 154 PP.) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MICHAEL HARRIS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wang Meng's career closely parallels that of Zhong Yicheng, the hero of this 
"modernist" novel first published in 1979: He joined the Communist Party as a 
teen-ager, was exiled to the countryside after something he had innocently 
written was branded as "rightist" in a 1957 purge, endured bitter years of 
manual labor and was finally rehabilitated after the Cultural Revolution. Wang, 
in addition, became China's minister of culture, only to be demoted again after 
last year's massacre in Tian An Men Square. 
</P>
<P>
Zhong is tormented by the question: What does it mean if the party is good but 
treats him badly? He decides that he must be bad. When his wife's love and the 
passage of time moderate his self-criticism, Zhong concludes that the good 
party made pardonable mistakes or, at worst, that his fate is a mystery. What 
to a Westerner would be the obvious answer -- that the party is tyrannical -- 
is simply unavailable to him, because his whole identity is bound up in the 
revolutionary idealism of his youth. 
</P>
<P>
In a valuable afterword, translator Wendy Larson shows how Wang, less naive 
than Zhong, hints at the unthinkable through the very structure of the novel, 
which exactly balances "positive" and "negative" episodes and bounces Zhong 
like a Ping-Pong ball between the paddles of logic and emotion. Wang implies 
that the intellectual, capable of logic, is always the potential enemy of 
revolutionary fervor; he has no place in communist society and must be kept too 
frightened, guilty or exhausted to perform his natural function: to think. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Book Review; Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
