<HEADLINE>
<P>
POP VIEWS; 
</P>
<P>
THE '70S REVISITED? YIKES!; 
</P>
<P>
YES, AM HITS SUCH AS 'KUNG FU FIGHTING' AND 'SPIRIT IN THE SKY' ARE BEING 
SALUTED IN A NEW 15-ALBUM SERIES. PERHAPS THOSE SONGS WEREN'T THAT BAD AFTER 
ALL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRIS WILLMAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
When Rhino Records announced late last year that it would be releasing a 
15-volume, 180-song series recollecting the disposable pop music of the early 
1970s, naysayers couldn't be blamed for wondering if there was even the 
slightest market for it. 
</P>
<P>
When it comes to '70s nostalgia, folks just don't bother getting out their 
usual rose-colored glasses. Americans as a culture hate the '70s -- especially 
the clothes, the trivial artifacts and the pop music. We tend to remember mood 
rings and wide collars and Grand Funk with only slightly more fondness and 
pride than, say, block-long gasoline lines. 
</P>
<P>
I found that out a couple of years ago when, presaging the current rage for 
post-Vietnam/pre-Reagan kitsch, I threw a '70s theme party. 
</P>
<P>
Guests were asked to come in proper period regalia: The wider the ties, the 
bigger the bells, the better. The house was a veritable time warp, from the Hot 
Chocolate music on the dance floor to the Tab in the refrigerator (nothing Lite 
allowed). It was meant to be both a celebration and an exorcism. 
</P>
<P>
A few dozen of the demonized did show up in their leisure suits and halter 
tops, in search of closure and healing. Some friends, however, refused to come 
to the party on grounds of moral principle, declining to dignify the despised 
decade with their presence, as if they were Nora Dunn and the '70s were Andrew 
Dice Clay. 
</P>
<P>
Others politely declined in the expectation that it would be "too depressing." 
Even some of the stalwarts who did come started moping around by themselves 
halfway through, as if hypnotically re-experiencing a particularly bad prom. 
</P>
<P>
A lot of people are having the same reaction to Rhino's "Super Hits of the '70s 
-- Have a Nice Day," a real Rorschach of a cassette and compact disc series. 
(Sorry, but it's not available in 8-track.) Like: Can't we let this stuff stay 
buried? 
</P>
<P>
A recent New York Times review took the standard critical view, with critic Jon 
Pareles declaring, "To me, the early 1970s was when rock bottomed out" and 
calling the Rhino compilation "a reminder of just how awful pop music was." 
</P>
<P>
Obviously Gary Stewart, vice president of A&amp;R for Rhino Records, doesn't 
agree. He sees the music in the 15-album series as in the same classic American 
Top 40 pop tradition as that of the '50s and '60s. Stewart, who compiled the 
series, thinks it's ludicrous to dismiss all the early-'70s hits just because 
they didn't meet the test of "significance." 
</P>
<P>
He has a point. There's a potential arrogance and a form of ageism in assigning 
an entire generation's ear candy -- the hits by generally inconsequential 
artists -- to the scrap heap, while celebrating equally lightweight hits from 
one's own time. 
</P>
<P>
The hits spotlighted in the Rhino series don't carry the artistic vision or 
musical energy of the great early-'60s works from Motown, Phil Spector, the 
Beatles or the Stones. The fact that everyone had bad haircuts doesn't help. 
</P>
<P>
But that doesn't mean they didn't still spotlight craft and provide lingering 
pleasures. There is indeed an overwhelming banality to much of what Rhino has 
revived, but in retrospect it's an endearing banality; even that which was most 
insincere and calculated has a long-lost kind of benign innocence to its 
calculation. 
</P>
<P>
No doubt about it, the '70s are back, mostly for camp's sake. First 
re-popularized amid England's acid-house scene, bell bottoms are now de rigueur 
for anyone who's truly hip today in L.A. Smiley faces can be spotted up and 
down Melrose. A Los Angeles dance club called 1970 specializes in period music 
ranging from Donna Summer to T. Rex. 
</P>
<P>
Bands cover '70s songs now the way they used to remake obscure '60s delicacies. 
A short list from recent memory: Doctor &amp; the Medics and Fuzzbox both 
recording "Spirit in the Sky" (see "Have a Nice Day Vol. 2"), Crowded House 
doing "Signs" (see Vol. 6) at the Pantages, John Hiatt singing "Kung Fu 
Fighting" (slated for a future volume) at McCabe's, Erasure resurrecting ABBA's 
"Gimme a Man After Midnight" at the Palace, and the Replacements slaughtering 
"Takin' Care of Business," "Rock and Roll All Night" and virtually every other 
hard-rock song of the period on their mid-'80s tours. 
</P>
<P>
In that spirit, Polydor Records is preparing an album of '70s hits updated by 
current artists -- including Living Colour's Corey Glover tackling Rufus' "Tell 
Me Something Good," Voice of the Beehive putting the sting on the Partridge 
Family's "I Think I Love You" and Hothouse Flowers opening up Johnny Nash's "I 
Can See Clearly Now." The inevitable title: "Guilty Pleasures." 
</P>
<P>
Camp is also the catchword for Rhino's "Super Hits of the '70s" series, which 
is not as inclusive as its name would indicate. Stewart decided to limit the 
series to acts that had only one or two hits in the Top 20 -- parameters that 
necessarily leave out album-oriented rock artists, along with acts that were 
actually strong enough to have, say, three or four hits. Thus you get Daddy 
Dewdrop but no Deep Purple; "Brandy" but not "Mandy." 
</P>
<P>
"The idea was to collect all the odds and ends -- 90% of which is no longer 
available," Stewart said. "In doing that, you sort of produce some music that's 
even more of its time, as opposed to music made by artists who had career 
longevity. 
</P>
<P>
"Most of the artists that had one hit, their vision or their musical style or 
their feel tapped right into that very moment and they probably weren't able to 
hit on that again. That makes the music more time-specific and dated, in a 
positive way." 
</P>
<P>
Stewart sees the early '70s as "the last hurrah" for the Top 40. 
</P>
<P>
"It was the last time people made records specifically for the singles market," 
Stewart said. " 'My Baby Loves Lovin',' 'Love Grows (Where My Rosemary Goes),' 
'United We Stand,' 'Gimme Dat Ding' -- all share the same lead singer, and all 
were made by non-pros. They were writers and musicians who decided to get 
together and make some single hits." 
</P>
<P>
Stewart is going to cut off the series, which is being released in 
chronological order, with Vol. 15 somewhere around 1975 -- "right up to when 
the first Ramones record came out," he said. "That's when 
</P>
<P>
Top 40 radio pretty much became totally invalid or unnecessary." 
</P>
<P>
Was Top 40 ever valid or necessary in the pre-punk, pre-disco period Stewart 
does cover? Even he admits the "Have a Nice Day" series is more for fun's sake 
than to argue a case for serious historical and artistic consideration. It's 
purposefully frothy -- and white. 
</P>
<P>
"R&amp;B records are kind of excluded from this series, basically because that 
music was genuinely good," Stewart explained. "Not that there aren't some good 
singles scattered in this series. But I think soul and R&amp;B reached a sort 
of apex during those years, and they're going to get their own series. (Rhino 
also has '70s disco and glitter-rock collections set for release.) You can 
actually take those records seriously." 
</P>
<P>
And you can't take "Have a Nice Day" seriously as representative of its period 
without its including any of what was uniquely great about the era -- Mott the 
Hoople, early Bowie and Alice Cooper, Al Green, Steely Dan, Roxy Music, the 
Philly soul sound, the Who, Marvin Gaye, et al. 
</P>
<P>
But even some of the most shallow music of the era holds its rewards -- at 
least in retrospect. There was every good reason in 1973 to truly hate the 
DeFranco Family's "Heartbeat -- It's a Lovebeat," which awkwardly combined bad 
melodrama and sickly sweetness in a theretofore unreckoned dosage. 
</P>
<P>
Yet you know that that's indeed little Tony DeFranco putting his 13-year-old 
heartbeat out on the line, a moment in time, without any sophisticated studio 
trickery to puff up his transparently thin vocal range. The song went to No. 3 
on the charts. It's doubtful you'll ever find such nakedness in a bubble-gum 
record again -- at least not in an age when technology makes everything so 
very, very professional. 
</P>
<P>
Some of these sides, it should be noted, are actually enduring or innovative 
quality work. Melanie used the Edwin Hawkins Singers on "Lay Down (Candles in 
the Rain)" nearly two decades before Madonna used the Andrae Crouch choir on 
"Like a Prayer," and to better effect. 
</P>
<P>
Hotlegs' "Neanderthal Man," with a pre-10cc incarnation of Godley &amp; Creme, 
probably has the most unusual production values -- tribal drums on top, vocals 
mixed way down -- of any single ever to hit the Top 40. 
</P>
<P>
Stories' "Brother Louie" went to No. 1 with a controversial interracial love 
theme. The Buoys' "Timothy" introduced cannibalism to the charts 20 years 
before warning labels. 
</P>
<P>
Less trend-setting but equally outstanding pop songs were Smith's "Baby It's 
You," Stealers Wheel's "Stuck in the Middle With You," Dobie Gray's "Drift 
Away" and Loudon Wainwright III's "Dead Skunk." 
</P>
<P>
You can even admire, if not necessarily like, the solid Tin Pan Alley 
craftsmanship of "It Never Rains in Southern California" or the suicidal "Alone 
Again (Naturally)," the earnest likes of which we'll rarely see on the 
Billboard charts again. 
</P>
<P>
Trade-offs have been made. Top 40 listeners and radio programmers have indeed 
come a long way in tolerance for dissonance and odd harmonic progressions 
("Purple Rain" could never have been a hit in the '70s), but almost always only 
if it has a dance beat. Weirdness and classicism both get homogenized by the 
mutual insistence of modern pop's standardized drum sound; heartbeat -- it's a 
machine beat. 
</P>
<P>
The hit parade of the Me Decade offered as much junk as the Madonna Decade, but 
it was an organic kind of junk, neither as wild-eyed as the quasi-hippie music 
that preceded it nor quite as greedily gumptious as the factory-made teen 
fodder it paved the way for. That may not mean that it might not be worthy of a 
good exorcism anyway, but a lingering -- or perhaps first-time -- fondness for 
the schlock monster is no cause for shame. 
</P>
<P>
Having Hamilton, Joe Frank &amp; Reynolds and Dr. Hook as part of your heritage 
is indeed a scourge, but it could be worse, thirty-something and 
late-twentysome-thing comrades -- you could have been born later and have 
"Hangin' Tough" for roots. In the words of the prophets: Hold your head up. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
